        <h2>2. ConstructConnect — Best lead generation network</h2>
        <p><strong>Pricing:</strong> Custom — typically $5,000–$15,000/yr depending on geography and modules</p>

        <p>ConstructConnect (which absorbed both iSqFt and SmartBid) is the largest commercial construction intelligence network in North America. GCs use it to find projects in preconstruction; subcontractors use it to find GCs who are bidding projects in their trade and area. The intelligence layer — project leads, bid invitations, plan rooms — sets it apart from pure bid management tools.</p>

        <p><strong>Who benefits most:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Subcontractors who depend on finding GC bid opportunities proactively, not waiting for invitations</li>
          <li>GCs who want early visibility into projects still in design phase</li>
          <li>Estimating teams who need digital plan distribution to their subcontractor lists</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>The cost challenge:</strong> ConstructConnect is expensive and renewal pricing is aggressive. Smaller subcontractors often find that the ROI requires landing only 1–2 additional jobs per year to justify the cost — which most do, but it requires actively working the platform.</p>

        <h2>3. PlanHub — Best free option for subcontractors</h2>
        <p><strong>Pricing:</strong> Free for subcontractors; GCs pay for bid solicitation access</p>

        <p>PlanHub has grown into a legitimate alternative to ConstructConnect in many regional markets by offering subcontractors free access. GCs post projects and plan sets; subs find opportunities and download plans without a subscription. For subcontractors not yet ready to invest in ConstructConnect, PlanHub is an excellent starting point — or a supplemental source of leads.</p>

        <p><strong>PlanHub strengths:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>No cost barrier for subs — create a profile and start finding projects immediately</li>
          <li>Clean plan room interface — downloading and reviewing plan sets is straightforward</li>
          <li>Growing regional coverage, particularly in the Southeast, Midwest, and Texas</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>Limitations:</strong> Project coverage is thinner than ConstructConnect in many markets. Large GCs tend to stick with BuildingConnected or ConstructConnect for solicitation, so some of the biggest opportunities don't appear on PlanHub.</p>

        <h2>4. Procore Bid Management — Best for Procore users</h2>
        <p><strong>Pricing:</strong> Module pricing within Procore's platform (contact sales)</p>

        <p>If your company already runs Procore for project management, its built-in Bid Management module is a natural addition. You solicit bids from subcontractors, level responses, and award without leaving the platform. The handoff from preconstruction to project is seamless since everything stays in Procore. The downside: it's not a standalone product and won't replace ConstructConnect for lead generation.</p>

        <h2>For subcontractors: how to manage multiple GC portals</h2>
        <p>One persistent challenge for commercial subs is that every GC uses a different platform — BuildingConnected, Procore, ConstructConnect, or a custom portal. Managing bid submissions across 5+ portals per week is genuinely painful. A few strategies:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Focus your solicitation sources:</strong> Be proactive on 1–2 platforms (usually ConstructConnect + either BuildingConnected or PlanHub) and track the rest passively</li>
          <li><strong>Use a CRM-style tracker:</strong> Even a simple spreadsheet tracking which projects you've bid, submission deadlines, and outcomes by GC is valuable</li>
          <li><strong>Designate a bid coordinator:</strong> For subs doing 10+ bids per month, one person whose job is tracking opportunities and managing ITB responses pays for itself quickly</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Bid management features that matter</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>ITB tracking:</strong> Know which subs opened your invitation, which declined, which are working on it</li>
          <li><strong>Digital plan rooms:</strong> Distribute plan sets without email attachments — track when subs download plans</li>
          <li><strong>Bid leveling:</strong> Compare sub responses across scope items in a structured spreadsheet view</li>
          <li><strong>Scope gaps:</strong> Flag when scope items lack sub coverage before bid day</li>
          <li><strong>Deadline management:</strong> Automated reminders to subs approaching submission deadlines</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Bottom line</h2>
        <p>GCs doing significant commercial work need BuildingConnected or ConstructConnect — the question is which one your local sub market uses most. In most major markets, BuildingConnected wins for solicitation; ConstructConnect wins for lead intelligence. Serious commercial estimating shops often use both.</p>

        <p>Subcontractors should start with PlanHub (free) and evaluate ConstructConnect once you've demonstrated a return from the free sources.</p>

